{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519539"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.76,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5474"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"403"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"3877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17415"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of fevers, chills, and abdominal pain. Her symptoms have been progressively worsening, and she now has right-sided abdominal pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and inability to eat. She has a history of diabetes mellitus and hypertension, for which she takes metformin and ramipril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 104/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. On abdominal examination, there is tenderness on deep palpation in the right costovertebral angle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 15.4 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 245 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine: 82 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrea: 6.2 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis demonstrates white blood cells, white cell casts, protein, and bacteria. Urine culture shows \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E growth, sensitive to ceftriaxone and ciprofloxacin. After five days of intravenous ceftriaxone, she continues to have fever and abdominal tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be performed next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain abdominal X-ray","Urine cytology","CT abdomen with contrast","MRI abdomen","Nuclear medicine renal scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of pyelonephritis that has failed to respond to appropriate antibiotic therapy. When patients remain febrile after 72 hours of appropriate antibiotics, complications such as renal or perinephric abscess must be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the imaging modality of choice for suspected renal or perinephric abscess. It can clearly delineate the extent of infection, identify collections requiring drainage, and detect other complications such as obstruction or emphysematous pyelonephritis. CT also helps guide potential drainage procedures if collections are identified. While ultrasound can be useful as an initial screening tool and is readily available, CT provides superior anatomical detail and is more reliable for identifying small collections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain abdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E has very limited utility in this scenario. While it might show radio-opaque stones or gas-forming infections, it lacks the sensitivity and detail needed to diagnose renal or perinephric abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect malignant cells in the urinary tract and would not be helpful in diagnosing complications of pyelonephritis. It is typically reserved for investigation of haematuria or suspected urothelial malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E, while providing excellent soft tissue detail, is not the first-line imaging modality for suspected renal abscess. It is more expensive, less readily available, and takes longer to perform than CT scanning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear medicine renal scan\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in the acute setting. While it can assess renal function and scarring, it lacks the anatomical detail needed to diagnose and guide management of renal or perinephric abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["CT abdomen with contrast is essential when pyelonephritis fails to respond to appropriate antibiotics to exclude renal or perinephric abscess.","Persistent fever after 72 hours of appropriate antibiotics for pyelonephritis should prompt investigation for complications.","Renal and perinephric abscesses require both imaging for diagnosis and drainage in addition to antibiotics for successful treatment."],"references":["Kranz J, Bartoletti R, Bruy\u00e8re F, Cai T, Geerlings S, K\u00f6ves B, et al. European Association of Urology Guidelines on Urological Infections: Summary of the 2024 Guidelines. European Urology. 2024 Jul 1;86(1):27\u201341.","Nelson Z, Tar\u0131k Aslan A, Beahm NP, Blyth M, Cappiello M, Casaus D, et al. Guidelines for the Prevention, Diagnosis, and Management of Urinary Tract Infections in Pediatrics and Adults: A WikiGuidelines Group Consensus Statement. JAMA Network Open. 2024 Nov 4;7(11):e2444495.","Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {25 Nov 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T21:32:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T21:36:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5474"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Ne